  1. within each subset (there arte more grouping variables than just country and year) calculate the total fertility rate (TFR) and the (ASFR-weighted) mean age at childbearing (MAB).
# From the above, it seems like we have a lot of potential
# grouping variables
HFC <- HFC %>% 
    group_by(
              Country, 
              Year1,
              Region, 
              Urban, 
              Origin, 
              Collection, 
              SourceType,
              RefCode,
              Vitality,
              AgeDef) %>% 
    mutate(TFR = sum(ASFR, na.rm = TRUE),
           MAB = sum(Age * ASFR, na.rm = TRUE) / TFR,
           TFRint = TFR - TFR %% .25) %>% # can change TFR interval 
    ungroup() %>% 
    group_by(TFRint) %>% 
    mutate(MABmax = MAB == max(MAB),
           MABmin = MAB == min(MAB),
           MABminmax = MABmax | MABmin,
           MABgroup = ifelse(MABmax, "max MAB",ifelse(MABmin,"min MAB",NA))) %>% 
    filter(MABminmax & TFR < 6) %>% 
    ungroup()
  1. now the goal is to draw a ridge plot of ASFR, where each ridge is a discrete bin of TFR in uniform intervals (maybe 8 - 15 different steps or so). Within each ridge there will be two distributions: The ASFR curve with the highest MAB and the one with the lowest MAB.
p <- ggplot(HFC,
            mapping = aes(x = Age, 
                         y = factor(TFRint, 
                                   levels = sort(unique(TFRint)), 
                                   ordered = TRUE)))
p + 
    geom_ridgeline(mapping = aes(x = Age, height = ASFR, fill = MABgroup),                               scale = 4, 
                            alpha = .6)
